<br>
While enabling the DMZ does solve the EQ LD problem, it opens up a whole new slate of security issues. I do not recommend using this option.<br>
<br>
A DMZ in the traditional sense means a section of your network with less security, so the public can have access to it. On the Linksys device, enabling the DMZ setting and using the IP of your PC means that anyone who makes a 'request' of your router, will have that request forwarded to your PC. It essentially makes your PC very vulnerable to attack. <br>
<br>
As a realworld example, on most corporate networks, Public webservers reside on a DMZ. The thing to keep in mind is that these DMZ's are often behind very powerful and flexible firewalls that only allow certain types of traffic to go into the DMZ (which is why you can get webpages from a server, but you might not be able to Ping a server). Linksys offers no such protection with its DMZ setting and simply allows all traffic to progress to your PC.<br>
<br>
Port Forwarding does the same thing, but is slightly more secure, as it restricts which ports are 'forwarded' to your PC. Unfortunately, the ports that you'd have to open to get EQ to run are fairly dangerous to leave open.<br>
<br>
Port Triggering is the option that is supposed to work, as it only keeps those ports open when the request comes from your own machine. It wouldn't allow someone from the outside to get at your machine, unless you initiated the 'session'. Unfortunately, as I stated before, I was unable to get the Triggering options to save on my Linksys (my model didn't have a firmware update available), and eventually gave up and bought a different product.<br>
<br>
